default5.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSaBTO recognises that further risk reduction measures may be proposed in the 
defaultfuture including the development and potential use of blood tests for detecting vCJD infection,
default which may help health services take more targeted action.  However in all cases SaBTO would wish to consider the potential implications for introduction of such measures not only for the services themselves but for each donor and recipient.  SaBTO acknowledges the important contribution to such potential future considerations provided by the Department of Health’s 2009 paper 
defaultMapping out the consequences of screening blood donations for PrP
defaultSc
default.  If ever a test were to be considered for introduction
default,
default SaBTO would consider 
defaultamongst other issues 
defaultthe levels of 
defaultsensitivity and specificity of the test (the highest possible would be 
defaultnecessary 
defaultwith the requirements set by the IVD Directive as a minimum), the availability of 
defaulta 
defaultconfirmatory assay (no test on donors could be considered without one), and the views of donors and recipients (particularly from heavily transfused individuals 
defaultincluding 
defaultsickle, thalassaemia and myelodysplasia patients).
